\begin_layout Standard
In the EMS model, where a scalar field is non-minimally coupled to electromagnet
ism, the background spacetime can become destabilized through a tachyonic
 instability, leading to the phenomenon of spontaneous scalarization in
 black holes.
 The corresponding action is described as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{1}{16\pi}\int d^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\left[R-2\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial^{\mu}\phi-f\left(\phi\right)F^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu}\right],\label{eq:Action}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the scalar field, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\mu\nu}=\partial_{\mu}A_{\nu}-\partial_{\nu}A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 denotes the electromagnetic field strength tensor, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 represents the electromagnetic field.
 It is important to note that to trigger spontaneous scalarization, the
 coupling function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 should satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(0\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\left(0\right)\equiv\left.df\left(\phi\right)/d\phi\right\vert _{\phi=0}=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2018wub,Fernandes:2019rez"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this paper, we focus on the specific exponential coupling function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\phi\right)=e^{\alpha\phi^{2}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 In this section, we present the numerical construction of scalarized KN
 black holes in the EMS model and investigate null circular geodesics (i.e.,
 light rings) within these scalarized KN black holes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tachyonic Instability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the scalar-free background, represented by KN black holes, the scalar
 perturbation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi$
\end_inset

 is governed by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\square-\mu_{\text{eff}}^{2}\right)\delta\phi=0,\label{eq:delta phi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{eff}}^{2}=\alpha F^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu}/2$
\end_inset

.
 In the Boyer-Linquist coordinates, the effective mass square can be expressed
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{\text{eff}}^{2}=-\frac{\alpha Q^{2}\left(r^{4}-6a^{2}r^{2}\cos^{2}\theta+a^{4}\cos^{4}\theta\right)}{\left(r^{2}+a^{2}\cos^{2}\theta\right)^{4}},\label{eq:effmass}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is the black hole charge, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 represents the ratio of black hole angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 to mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv J/M$
\end_inset

).
 Notably, tachyonic instabilities arise in the presence of a negative effective
 mass square 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{eff}}^{2}<0$
\end_inset

, which could induce scalarized black holes from the scalar-free background.
 When restricted to the equatorial plane, the effective mass square reduces
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{eff}}^{2}=-\alpha Q^{2}/r^{4}$
\end_inset

, which coincides with the RN black hole case 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2018wub,Guo:2021zed"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the RN black hole background, it has demonstrated that the tachyonic
 instabilities near the black hole event horizon can be strong enough to
 trigger spontaneous scalarization.
 By analogy, we expect similar tachyonic instabilities to induce scalarized
 KN black holes from the KN black hole background.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To investigate the onset of spontaneous scalarization in KN black holes,
 we need to solve the linear perturbation equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:delta phi}\right)$
\end_inset

 for zero-modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The presence of these zero-modes often indicates the existence of scalarized
 black hole solutions.
 Specifically, the zero-modes correspond to bifurcation points in the parameter
 space, marking the onset of scalarized KN black holes.
 In the latter part of this section, we will discuss the numerical scheme
 employed to find the zero-modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rotating Black Hole Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations of motion for the metric field 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, the scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and the electromagnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by varying the action 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:Action}\right)$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}Rg_{\mu\nu} & =2T_{\mu\nu},\nonumber \\
\square\phi-\frac{\alpha}{2}\phi e^{\alpha\phi^{2}}F^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu} & =0,\label{eq:nonlinearEOMs}\\
\partial_{\mu}\left(\sqrt{-g}e^{\alpha\phi^{2}}F^{\mu\nu}\right) & =0,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the energy-momentum tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu}=\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial_{\nu}\phi-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}\left(\partial\phi\right)^{2}+e^{\alpha\phi^{2}}\left(F_{\mu\rho}F_{\nu}^{\text{ }\rho}-\frac{1}{4}g_{\mu\nu}F_{\rho\sigma}F^{\rho\sigma}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2015gia,Delgado:2016jxq,Herdeiro:2020wei"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we consider stationary, axisymmetric and asymptotically-flat black hole
 solutions with the generic ansatz 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ds^{2} & =-e^{2F_{0}}Ndt^{2}+e^{2F_{1}}\left(\frac{dr^{2}}{N}+r^{2}d\theta^{2}\right)+e^{2F_{2}}r^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\left(d\varphi^{2}-\frac{W}{r^{2}}dt\right)^{2},\nonumber \\
A_{\mu}dx^{\mu} & =\left(A_{t}-A_{\varphi}\frac{W}{r^{2}}\sin\theta\right)dt+A_{\varphi}\sin\theta d\varphi\text{ and }\phi=\phi\left(r,\theta\right),\label{eq:ansatz}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\equiv1-1/r_{H}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{H}$
\end_inset

 is the black hole horizon.
 Here, the metric functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 are assumed to depend solely on the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 By substituting the ansatz 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:ansatz}\right)$
\end_inset

 into eqn.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:nonlinearEOMs}\right)$
\end_inset

, we derive a set of nonlinear partial differential equations for the metric
 functions.
 The solutions of the partial differential equations can describe scalarized
 KN black holes with a nontrivial profile of the scalar field or KN black
 holes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the stationary spacetime, two Killing vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 are present, and their combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\partial_{t}+\Omega_{H}\partial\varphi$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{H}$
\end_inset

 is the angular velocity of the black hole horizon, is both orthogonal to
 and null at the horizon.
 Consequently, the surface gravity 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{2}=-\left(\nabla_{\mu}\xi_{\nu}\right)\left(\nabla^{\mu}\xi^{\nu}\right)/2$
\end_inset

, and it is related to the Hawking temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{H}$
\end_inset

 as given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2015gia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{H}=\frac{\kappa}{2\pi}=\frac{1}{4\pi r_{H}}e^{F_{0}\left(r_{H},\theta\right)-F_{1}\left(r_{H},\theta\right)}.\label{eq:TH}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the EMS model, the black hole entropy is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $S=A_{H}/4$
\end_inset

, where the area of the horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{H}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{H}=2\pi r_{H}^{2}\int_{0}^{\pi}d\theta\sin\theta e^{F_{1}\left(r_{H},\theta\right)+F_{2}\left(r_{H},\theta\right)}.\label{eq:Ah}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various physical quantities, such as the black hole mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the black hole charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, the black hole angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, the electrostatic potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 and the horizon angular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{H}$
\end_inset

, can be determined by studying the asymptotic behavior of the metric functions
 at the event horizon and spatial infinity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2015gia,Delgado:2016jxq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.A_{t}\right\vert _{r=r_{H}} & \sim0,\quad\left.W\right\vert _{r=r_{H}}\sim r_{H}^{2}\Omega_{H},\nonumber \\
\left.A_{t}\right\vert _{r=\infty} & \sim\Phi-\frac{Q}{r},\quad\left.W\right\vert _{r=\infty}\sim\frac{2J}{r},\quad\left.e^{2F_{0}}N\right\vert _{r=\infty}\sim1-\frac{2M}{r}.\label{eq:asymptotic behaviors}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Moreover, these physical quantities are related by the Smarr relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2015gia,Guo:2021zed,Fernandes:2022gde"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M=2T_{H}S+2\Omega_{H}J+\Phi Q,\label{eq:smarr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which enables us to assess the accuracy of our numerical black hole solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Light Ring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Light rings are null circular geodesics in the black hole spacetime and
 plays a crucial role in strong gravitational lensing and in the formation
 of black hole images.
 For simplicity, we focus on light rings on the equatorial plane.
 On the equatorial plane, the motion of photons is described by the Lagrangian
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=-\frac{e^{2F_{0}}N\dot{t}^{2}}{2}+\frac{e^{2F_{1}}}{2N}\dot{r}^{2}+\frac{e^{2F_{2}}r^{2}}{2}\left(\dot{\phi}-\frac{W}{r^{2}}\dot{t}\right)^{2},\label{eq:photon Lag}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where dots denote derivatives with respect to an affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The conserved energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of photons, associated with the Killing vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, respectively, are expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E & =\left(e^{2F_{0}}N-e^{2F_{2}}\frac{W^{2}}{r^{2}}\right)\dot{t}+e^{2F_{2}}W\dot{\varphi},\nonumber \\
L & =e^{2F_{2}}\left(r^{2}\dot{\phi}-W\dot{t}\right).\label{eq:conserved quantitites}
\end{align}

\end_inset

By substituting eqn.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:conserved quantitites}\right)$
\end_inset

 into eqn.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:photon Lag}\right)$
\end_inset

, the constancy of the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=0$
\end_inset

 reduces to the radial equation for photons, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{r}^{2}+V_{\text{eff}}=0\text{,}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{eff}}\leq0$
\end_inset

 for null geodesics.
 Here, the effective potential is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\text{eff}}=L^{2}e^{-2F_{1}}N\left[\frac{e^{-2F_{2}}}{r^{2}}-\frac{e^{-2F_{0}}}{N}\left(\frac{1}{b}-\frac{W}{r^{2}}\right)^{2}\right],\label{eq:effV}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b\equiv L/E$
\end_inset

 is the impact parameter.
 Thus, for a photon with an impact parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{c}$
\end_inset

, it would follow a circular orbit at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{c}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{eff}}\left(b_{c},r_{c}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}V_{\text{eff}}\left(b_{c},r_{c}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To facilitate further analysis, we can factorize the effective potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{eff}}$
\end_inset

 as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cunha:2016bjh"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\text{eff}}=-L^{2}e^{-2F_{1}-2F_{0}}\left(\frac{1}{b}-H_{+}\right)\left(\frac{1}{b}-H_{-}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{+}=\frac{\sqrt{e^{2F_{0}-2F_{2}}Nr^{2}}+W}{r^{2}},\quad H_{-}=-\frac{\sqrt{e^{2F_{0}-2F_{2}}Nr^{2}}-W}{r^{2}}.\label{eq:H+-}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notably, the two redefined effective potentials, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{-}$
\end_inset

, are independent of the impact parameter and describe prograde and retrograde
 motion of photons on the equatorial plane, respectively.
 For a null geodesic, the effective potentials 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{-}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}<b^{-1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{-}>b^{-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}\geq H_{-}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, a null circular geodesic at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{c}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a local extremum of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{-}$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}H_{+}\left(r_{c}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}H_{-}\left(r_{c}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}^{2}H_{+}\left(r_{c}\right)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}^{2}H_{+}\left(r_{c}\right)<0$
\end_inset

 indicate stable and unstable prograde light rings, respectively, while
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}^{2}H_{-}\left(r_{c}\right)<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}^{2}H_{-}\left(r_{c}\right)>0$
\end_inset

 correspond to stable and unstable retrograde light rings, respectively.
 It is worth mentioning that in the static case with 
\begin_inset Formula $W=0$
\end_inset

, light rings can be solely determined by either 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{-}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{+}=-H_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Numerical Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we utilize pseudospectral methods to numerically solve the
 linear partial differential equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:delta phi}\right)$
\end_inset

 for zero-modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and a set of coupled nonlinear partial differential equations for scalarized
 KN black holes.
 Pseudospectral methods are a well-established approach for solving partial
 differential equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "boyd2001chebyshev"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 They approximate the exact solution by a finite linear combination of basis
 functions.
 Notably, as the number of degrees-of-freedom increases, pseudospectral
 methods exhibit an exponential convergence rate for well-behaved functions,
 in contrast to the linear or polynomial convergence of finite difference
 or finite element methods.
 Recently, these pseudospectral methods have demonstrated successful application
s in searching for black hole solutions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fernandes:2022gde,Lai:2023gwe,Burrage:2023zvk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as well as computing black hole quasinormal modes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jansen:2017oag,Gan:2019jac,Chung:2023zdq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For technical details of pseudospectral methods in the context of black
 hole physics, interested readers can refer to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fernandes:2022gde"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the numerical implementation, we introduce a new radial variable given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{\sqrt{r^{2}-r_{H}^{2}}-r_{H}}{\sqrt{r^{2}-r_{H}^{2}}+r_{H}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which allows us to map the event horizon and spatial infinity to 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 By performing series expansions of the solutions at the event horizon,
 we obtain the corresponding boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{x}\delta\phi=\partial_{x}F_{0}=\partial_{x}F_{1}=\partial_{x}F_{2}=\partial_{x}\phi=\partial_{x}A_{\varphi}=A_{t}=W-\Omega_{H}=0\text{ at }x=-1.\label{eq:bdx0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Moreover, due to the flatness at the spatial infinity, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\phi=F_{0}=F_{1}=F_{2}=\phi=A_{\varphi}=A_{t}-\Phi=W=0\text{ at }x=1.\label{eq:bdx1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

On the other hand, the regularity on the symmetric axis imposes the conditions
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\theta}\delta\phi=\partial_{\theta}F_{0}=\partial_{\theta}F_{1}=\partial_{\theta}F_{2}=\partial_{\theta}\phi=\partial_{\theta}A_{\varphi}=\partial_{\theta}A_{t}=\partial_{\theta}W=0\text{ at }\theta=0\,\text{and }\pi.\label{eq:bdtheta0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since all solutions are symmetric with respect to the equatorial plane,
 we can restrict the analysis to the upper half domain with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\theta\leq\pi/2$
\end_inset

, and hence replace the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi$
\end_inset

 boundary condition in eqn.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bdtheta0}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\theta}\delta\phi=\partial_{\theta}F_{0}=\partial_{\theta}F_{1}=\partial_{\theta}F_{2}=\partial_{\theta}\phi=\partial_{\theta}A_{\varphi}=\partial_{\theta}A_{t}=\partial_{\theta}W=0\text{ at }\theta=\pi/2.\label{eq:bdtheta1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Consequently, eqns.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bdx0}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bdx1}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bdtheta0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:bdtheta1}\right)$
\end_inset

 serve as boundary conditions for solving the partial differential equations.
 Additionally, the absence of conical singularities requires 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}=F_{2}$
\end_inset

 on the symmetric axis, which can be used to verify our numerical results
 as well as the Smarr relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herdeiro:2015gia,Herdeiro:2020wei"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the compactified radial coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the functions of interest, which are collectively denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=\left\{ F_{0},F_{1},F_{2},W,A_{t},A_{\varphi},\phi,\delta\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

, can be decomposed into a spectral expansion,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}^{\left(k\right)}=%TCIMACRO{\dsum\limits _{i=0}^{N_{x}-1}}%
%BeginExpansion
{\displaystyle \sum\limits _{i=0}^{N_{x}-1}}%EndExpansion%
%TCIMACRO{\dsum\limits _{j=0}^{N_{\theta}-1}}%
%BeginExpansion
{\displaystyle \sum\limits _{j=0}^{N_{\theta}-1}}%EndExpansion
\alpha_{ij}^{\left(k\right)}T_{i}\left(x\right)\cos\left(2j\theta\right).\label{eq:sexpansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 represent the resolutions in the radial and angular coordinates, respectively,
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Chebyshev polynomial, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}^{\left(k\right)}$
\end_inset

 are the spectral coefficients.
 To ensure numerical precision and efficiency, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N_{x},N_{\theta}\right)=\left(22,5\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N_{x},N_{\theta}\right)=\left(42,8\right)$
\end_inset

 for the subsequent numerical computations of the zero-modes and the metric
 functions, respectively.
 To determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}^{\left(k\right)}$
\end_inset

, we substitute the spectral expansions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:sexpansion}\right)$
\end_inset

 into the partial differential equations and discretize the resulting equations
 at the Gauss-Chebyshev points.
 This process reduces the partial differential equations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to a finite system of algebraic equations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 We then solve these algebraic equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by a standard iterative Newton-Raphson method, where the resulting linear
 system of equations is solved using the built-in command LinearSolve in
 Mathematica.
\end_layout

